A '''bored cylindrical lock''' is a [[lockset]] which is installed by boring two circular holes in the [[door]]. [[Door handle]]s may also use the same installation. [[File:Mis fotos de celular 019.jpg|thumb|right|250px|]]
==Installation== [[File:Bored cylindrical lockset door preparation.svg|thumb|right|250px|Typical preparation required for installation of a bored cylindrical lockset.]] Two holes are bored, perpendicular to one another, into the [[door]]. The "face bore" is the larger hole which is bored into the door face and a smaller "edge bore" hole is bored into the door edge. The edge may require additional preparation to receive the latch assembly, typically by [[router (woodworking)|routing]] or [[chisel]]ing a shallow mortise.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thisoldhouse.com/how-to/how-to-install-lockset |title=How to Install a Lockset |author1=Gibson, Scott |author2=Abram, Norm |author-link2=Norm Abram |publisher=This Old House |accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref> Some commercially-sold doors may come prepared to receive one or more bored cylindrical locks, such as entry doors, which typically require both a door knob and [[dead bolt]].
In the United States, typically, the face bore is sized from {{convert|1.5|to|2.125|in|cm}} in diameter and is centered at {{convert|2.375|or|2.75|in|cm}} from the leading edge of the door. This distance is referred to as the "backset."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.directdoorhardware.com/door_latch_backset.htm |title=What is Backset |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=Direct Door Hardware |accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref> Other, less popular, backsets are at {{convert|3.75|and|5|in|cm}}. Residential doors are normally prepared with a {{convert|2.375|in|cm|adj=on}} backset and commercial doors have a {{convert|2.75|in|cm|adj=on}} backset. The edge bore is typically centered on the edge.
== History == The cylindrical lock was invented by [[Walter Schlage]]<ref Name="Derdak">{{cite book |title= International Directory of Company Histories, Volume 82 |last= Derdak & Grant |first= |authorlink= |author2=Thomas Derdak|author3=Tina Grant |year= 2006 |publisher= St. James Press |location= University of California |isbn= 1-55862-586-0 |page= 330 |pages= |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=V-K6AAAAIAAJ&q=%22Bored+cylindrical+lock%22&dq=%22Bored+cylindrical+lock%22}}</ref> in 1923.<ref>{{cite patent |country=US |number=1674841 |status=granted |title=Door Lock |gdate=26 June 1928 |fdate=20 August 1923 |inventor=Schlage, Walter R. |assign1=Schlage Lock Co.}}</ref> The '''bored cylindrical lock''' arose from a need for a more cost-effective method of locking doors. The previous norm, the [[mortise lock]], is a more complex device, and its higher manufacturing cost as well as its more labor-intensive installation make the bored cylindrical lock an ideal substitute, both in price and functionality. Because the mortise lock has a larger lock case, a larger and more complex volume must be removed from the door before it can be installed, but the mortise lock may offer additional functions compared to a cylindrical lock; for instance, the mortise lock may include a deadbolt in a single unit, while the cylindrical lock would require separate face bores for a deadbolt and doorknob.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sargentlock.com/file_broker.php?document_id=6641 |title=Basic Technical Fundamentals of Builders Hardware: Mortise, Bored and Auxiliary Locks |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2016 |publisher=Sargent, an Assa Abloy Company |accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref> The 1923 patent evolved from an earlier Schlage patent filed in 1920<ref>{{cite patent |country=US |number=1456041 |status=granted |title=Door Lock |gdate=22 May 1923 |fdate=12 April 1920 |inventor=Schlage, Walter R. |assign1=Schlage Manufacturing Company}}</ref> for a lock whose installation required a face bore and surface [[rabbet]], which simplified door preparation compared to a mortise lock.
